cs.IT, cs.SI, cs.DS, cs.LG, cs.NI. 

The paper deals with information theory and communication, specifically the feedback capacity of finite-state channels. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely category. The paper also introduces a new technique called the $Q$-contexts, which involves constructing a directed graph, suggesting that it could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also uses a fixed point principle of the BCJR equation, which is a statistical signal processing technique, indicating that it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture).
